[{"question":"And as Rupert Murdoch prepares to address members of parliament in Britain tomorrow, how serious is this moment for him and his company?","answer":"I think it\u0027s dreadfully serious for Rupert Murdoch, and his family and his company.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":31,"aSentId":32},{"question":"Why weren\u0027t they asking those questions?","answer":"Well, I\u0027m sure that the editors would be asking those question.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":50,"aSentId":51},{"question":"I mean would you expect him to?","answer":"No, I would not.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":56,"aSentId":57},{"question":"I would expect he might have asked the question, how -- how are we getting all of this wonderful stuff?","answer":"Let\u0027s turn to Porter Bibb here.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":64,"aSentId":65},{"question":"Is the newspaper division for him now in Britain simply not making enough money to make it worth saving in a crisis like this?","answer":"Well, he\u0027s got to address several constituencies on this issue.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":71,"aSentId":72},{"question":"Was your information that the Murdochs were considering selling their newspaper division?","answer":"No, I mean, we have no idea.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":83,"aSentId":84},{"question":"Do you see a time coming as newspapers diminish in their importance, when the Murdoch\u0027s Corporation, News Corporation, with or without the Murdochs, Views newspapers as disposable assets to let them focus on television and movies, which make more money?","answer":"Well, I mean, there\u0027s clearly an I affinity for newspapers by Rupert Murdoch.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":96,"aSentId":97},{"question":"Do you think that these shares are now undervalued, given the scale of this crisis?","answer":"OHEN: Yes, News Corp has lost over $8 billion of value since the crisis erupted in the last few weeks.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":105,"aSentId":106},{"question":"I mean again, looking at him dispassionately, do you think he\u0027s been primarily a force for good or a force for not so good in the media?","answer":"I think he\u0027s probably led a race to the bottom.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":117,"aSentId":118},{"question":"And in terms of exposure to the American part of the company, am I right in thinking that if that is proven, if there were bribes being paid, either anonymously or in fake names, or whatever it may be, if it were paid by News International, a British company, does that still impact on the American part of the business?","answer":"There\u0027s two distinctions here.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":124,"aSentId":125},{"question":"Or do you worry conversely that all this attention on this means there may be further attacks on freedom of the press?","answer":"Well, I think you have to separate the questions.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":133,"aSentId":134},{"question":"How are they dealing with this, do you think?","answer":"Well, you know, Piers, I just got a call an hour ago, and Rupert wanted to tell me personally that you know he\u0027s not OK.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":160,"aSentId":161},{"question":"How do you think he will deal with this?","answer":"I think he will be -- I mean the one thing about Rupert is that -- yes, he can be ruthless, but actually we can just talk about this -- I think one -- he\u0027s ruthless, but also entrepreneurial.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":209,"aSentId":210},{"question":"So what do you think went wrong here?","answer":"Well, Piers, number one, thank you for having me.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":251,"aSentId":252},{"question":"Why?","answer":"OK.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":324,"aSentId":325},{"question":"What did you feel when you watched those images?","answer":"Well, I felt a huge disappointment.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":372,"aSentId":373},{"question":"Or should she be allowed to lead the life she wants to lead?","answer":"Of course she should lead the life she wants to lead.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":390,"aSentId":391},{"question":"What does that mean?","answer":"It means that public opinion had been driven I think by the saturation coverage on television and all of the commentary, so that most people were directed to believe -- and, you know, I\u0027m sure you wouldn\u0027t deny the fact you were directing people to think this -- that this woman killed her child.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":420,"aSentId":421},{"question":"Jealous?","answer":"Tell me about the -- I also love the fact that even then you could tell that you had this kind of fire brand attitude.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":445,"aSentId":446},{"question":"Was it as simple as that?","answer":"You know, Piers, it\u0027s so complicated.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":468,"aSentId":469},{"question":"When you get criticized, what do you think is the biggest misconception about you?","answer":"Oh, Piers, come on, you\u0027ve been through this, I\u0027m sure.","docId":"110718pmt","qSentId":514,"aSentId":515}]